{{multiple image
 | width= 240
 | direction = vertical
 | image1 = Motorfrachtschiff Anroma (ENI 02323909) mit Leichter Quatro (ENI 02332894) am Deutschen Eck, Koblenz-8687.jpg
 | image2 = Motorfrachtschiff Anroma (ENI 02323909) mit Leichter Quatro (ENI 02332894) am Deutschen Eck, Koblenz-8679.jpg
 | footer = '''Blue sign''' activated, during [[starboard]] passing
 }}
[[Image:Blaue Tafel mit weißem Funkellicht Binnenschiff 02.JPG|thumb|240px|right|Rotating-style blue sign laying flat when not active.  There is a 5&nbsp;cm white border and the light is in the centre]]
A '''blue sign''' or '''blue board''' is used by inland waterways vessels within the [[Trans-European Inland Waterway network]] when performing a special manoeuvre or passing on the starboard side.  On navigable [[waterways]] vessels normally pass each other on the [[Port and starboard|port]]-side, so the display of the blue sign and flashing white light signal intention to pass each other on the [[starboard]]-side.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.varendoejesamen.nl/sites/default/files/folders/EN%20The%20Blue%20Sign.pdf|title=The Blue Sign|year=2014|author1=Varen doe je samen!|author2=Numericanal|author3=Department of Waterways|author4=Rotterdam Harbour|author5=Groningen Seaports|author6=Amsterdam Harbour|author7=Koninklijke Schuttevaer|author8=ANWB|author9=Watersportverbond|author10=HISWA|author11=SRN|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150723230511/http://www.varendoejesamen.nl/sites/default/files/folders/EN%20The%20Blue%20Sign.pdf|archivedate=2015-07-23|df=}}</ref> This process is known as '''blue boarding''' or historically '''blue flagging'''.<ref name="harwood">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yG91CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA162|chapter=Appendix|title=Cruising the Inland Waterways of France & Belgium|edition=18th|isbn=978-1-326-11343-8|publisher=[[The Cruising Association]]|year=2015|first=Margaret|last=Harwood|page=162|quote=Blue Flagging. Especially on rivers, look out for ships or barges with a blue flag or board display on the starboard side of the wheelhouse.}}</ref><ref name="martin">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yTJLAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT161|title=The European Waterways: A User's Guide|first=Marian|last=Martin|page=161|publisher=A & C Black|year=2013|isbn=9781472901545|quote=… meetings are conducted what is colloquially known as 'blue boarding'}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=1rWcotTBFdEC&pg=PA138|work=Motor Boating & Sailing|date=April 1974|page=138|title=Cruising Europe|first=Fred C.|last=Clark Jr.|issn=1531-2623|publisher=Whiting, John R.|editor-first=Peter R.|editor-last=Smyth|quote=Lots of blue flagging, as upbound vessels try to stay in the shadow of the current, and call for starboard-to-starboard passing.}}</ref><ref name="pilkington">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HuI7AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA6|title=Small boat through Germany|first=Roger|last=Pilkington|publisher=St. Martin's Press|year=1964|format=originally published 1963|quote=we had already rigged an arrangement for blue flagging—a flag of Oxbridge blue run up on the starboard side being an indication that a vessel proceeding downstream on the Rhine, Meuse, Main, Neckar, Lahn, Ems, Weser, Elbe or Seine wishes to meet an approaching ship starboard to starboard instead of port to port. Or, more simply, that the skipper is keeping to the left instead of the right because he wants the current, or can't steer properly}}</ref>

The ''{{lang|fr|[[Code Européen des Voies de la Navigation Intérieure]]}}'' (CEVNI) regulations require upstream vessels operating on the opposite side to display a light-blue sign and scintillating (flashing) white light.<ref name="cevni-6.06">{{cite book|url=http://www.unece.org/fileadmin/DAM/trans/doc/finaldocs/sc3/ECE-TRANS-SC3-115-Rev.5e_WEB.pdf|title=European Code for Inland Waterways|edition=5th|publisher=[[United Nations Economic Commission for Europe]]|author=Inland Transport Committee|author2=Working Party on Inland Water Transport|isbn=978-92-1-117090-0|issue=ECE/TRANS/SC.3/115/Rev.5|chapter=Rules of the Road|pages=53|quote=Article 6.04 – Meeting: Normal rules … 4. Vessels proceeding upstream which leave the course of those proceeding downstream on their starboard side shall in good time and to starboard: … Display a light blue board in conjunction with a bright scintillating white light.|accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>  Article 3.03 states that the board must be rectangular and 1-metre × 1-metre for large vessels, or 0.6-metres × 0.6-metres for small vessels.<ref name="cevni-3.03">{{cite book|url=http://www.unece.org/fileadmin/DAM/trans/doc/finaldocs/sc3/ECE-TRANS-SC3-115-Rev.5e_WEB.pdf|title=European Code for Inland Waterways|edition=5th|publisher=United Nations Economic Commission for Europe|author=Inland Transport Committee|author2=Working Party on Inland Water Transport|isbn=978-92-1-117090-0|issue=ECE/TRANS/SC.3/115/Rev.5|pages=20|chapter=Visual Signals (Marking) on Vessels|quote=Article 3.03 – Boards, flags and pennants … rectangular. … (a) … neither the length nor the width is less than 1 m or, in the case of small craft, less than 0.60 m;|accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>

The presence and status of the blue sign is transmitted by the ship's Inland-[[Automatic Identification System]] (Inland-AIS) transponder to other vessels.  The status of the sign is transmitted using two bits of the "regional application flags"/"special manoeuvre field" in the AIS position reports.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.ccr-zkr.org/files/documents/ris/ais20_e.pdf|title=Central Commission for the Navigation of the Rhine (CCNR) Test Standard Inland AIS|edition=2.0|date=16 October 2012|accessdate=22 July 2015|series=Vessel Tracking and Tracing Standard for Inland Navigation|pages=12–13}}</ref>  This must be transmitted every ten seconds.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/PDF/?uri=CELEX:32007R0415&from=EN|title=Commission Regulation (EC) No 415/2007|format=concerning the technical specifications for vessel tracking and tracing systems referred to in Article 5 of Directive 2005/44/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council on harmonised river information services (RIS) on inland waterways in the Community of 13 March 2007|date=23 April 2007|accessdate=22 July 2015|work=Official Journal of the European Union|quote=1.3.2. Navigation, short-term ahead … Navigation a short-term ahead is the decision phase in the navigation process. … — intention (blue sign),}}</ref>

