'''György P. Bulányi''' (Budapest, 9 January 1919 – Budapest, June 6, 2010{{sfn|Zala Lama|2010}}) was a [[Piarist]] priest, teacher, and leader of the [[Bokor (Catholic)|Bokor]] Catholic youth discipleship movements in [[Religion in Croatia|Croatia]] and [[Religion in Hungary|Hungary]] which faced strong suppression from the Hungarian [[Hungarian People's Republic|communist government]] and Catholic hierarchy for their advocacy of [[conscientious objection]].

== Early life ==

Bulányi graduated from the College of Teacher Education, the College of Paleontology, and then the [[Eötvös Loránd University|Pázmány Péter University of Sciences]].{{cn|date=April 2018}} In 1943 he was ordained a priest in the Piarist Order.{{sfn|Ramet|2014|p=113}}{{sfn|Zala Lama|2010}}{{sfn|Partizano|2010}} He then taught in a [[Catholic school|Piarist high school]] serving [[Sátoraljaújhely]], [[Tata, Hungary|Tata]], and [[Debrecen]].
In March 1945, a [[Croatian Province of the Society of Jesus|Croatian Jesuit]] named [[Kolaković]]s came to Hungary to form [[base communities]] of youth with the permission of [[József Mindszenty]], bishop of [[Veszprém]]. {{sfn|Gyula Havasy|1993}} Kolakovićs viewed the model of base communities or [[cell groups]] as a survival strategy in the face of likely [[Persecution of Christians in the Eastern Bloc|communist suppression]] where leaders might be unavailable.{{sfn|Partizano|2010}} Bulányi and Kolakovićs collaborated to in the [[Formation (Catholic)|formation]] of the high school students who joined this community, and the group came to be called Bokor{{sfn|Gyula Havasy|1993}} meaning "[[bush (plant)|bush]]".{{sfn|Ramet|2014|p=100}} They were sometimes also called Bulányists.{{sfn|Gyula Havasy|1993}}

== Bokor ==

Bokor was focused on following [[Jesus]] and cultivating a love for Jesus.{{sfn|Adogame|Olson|Obinna|Vincett|2016|p=149f}}{{sfn|Gyula Havasy|1993}} Bokor taught principles of [[altruism]], [[humility]], [[voluntary poverty]], service to the poor, and [[Christian pacifism]]. Bokor opposed all involvement in the military and use of force.{{sfn|Adogame|Olson|Obinna|Vincett|2016|p=149f}}{{sfn|Gyula Havasy|1993}} It was a [[Christian movement|movement]] designed for [[exponential growth]], intending to train participants to start their own [[Leaderless resistance|leaderless]] [[cell group]] of 4–12 friends.{{sfn|Gyula Havasy|1993}}{{sfn|Partizano|2010}}<ref>See also {{harvtxt|Ramet|2014|p=100}}</ref> The movement was [[egalitarian]], offering all participants the opportunity to share their opinions, and group [[prayer]]s were performed by [[taking turns]].{{sfn|Gyula Havasy|1993}}

In 1949, Bulányi wrote a pamphlet {{lang|hu|Régi Írás}} (Old Scripture) on behalf of a group calling itself {{lang|hu|Bokor-Öko}} (Bush-Eco). The pamphlet asserted that humanity has a [[moral responsibility]] to respect [[nature]], [[Conservation (ethic)|preserve]] the [[natural environment]], and consider the impacts of actions on [[future generation]]s. This is one of the earliest documents of the modern [[environmental movement]] in Hungary.{{sfn|Tibor Valuch|2001}}

Bokor opposed the [[atheist]] [[communist]] ideology of the Hungarian state under [[Mátyás Rákosi]],{{sfn|Zala Lama|2010}} and continued to clash specifically on the topic of pacifism. The Hungarian State Church Office to the Bishop warned them that this position would not be tolerated, but Bokor held firm on this issue.<ref name="Wagner" />{{sfn|Partizano|2010}} The Hungarian government viewed the Bokor community as an illegal anti-state organization,{{cn|date=April 2018}} and sentenced Bulányi to [[life imprisonment]] in 1952.{{sfn|Ramet|2014|p=113}}{{sfn|Zala Lama|2010}} He escaped in October 1956 during the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956|Hungarian revolution]]{{sfn|Ramet|2014|p=113}} and became a [[parish priest]] in downtown [[Budapest]].{{sfn|Zala Lama|2010}} However, he was arrested again in April 1958 and later released again in 1960.{{sfn|Zala Lama|2010}} At this time, he was one of the most controversial figures in Hungarian Catholicism.{{sfn|Zala Lama|2010}} He then worked as an unskilled laborer while he wrote a book, ''Seek the kingdom of God!''{{sfn|Partizano|2010}}

Bokor grew throughout the 1960s and became even more visible after 1970,{{sfn|Murzaku|2015|p=173}} despite ongoing suppression from both the government and the Catholic hierarchy.{{cn|date=April 2018}} For those interested in deeper discipleship, Bokor offered a 5 year theological course involving about 78–80 [[Spiritual practice|spiritual exercises]] per year.{{sfn|Gyula Havasy|1993}}
In 1989, Bokor had 185 leaders, 35 of whom were priests.{{sfn|Gyula Havasy|1993}} The movement was connected to the base communities of Latin American [[liberation theology]].{{sfn|Partizano|2010}} Bokor continued to be suppressed by the Hungarian government until 1990.{{sfn|Ramet|2014|p=104}}

== Conscientious objection advocacy ==

From the end of the 1970s into 1981, Bulányi became more vocal in preaching pacifism and [[conscientious objection]] publicly, and the practice increased markedly.{{sfn|Allen|2002|p=162}}{{sfn|Miszlivetz|1999|p=11}} Dozens of Bokor members were imprisoned for their pacifist stance.{{sfn|Murzaku|2015|p=173}}{{sfn|Miszlivetz|1999|p=11}} [[Catholic Church in Hungary|Hungarian Catholic]] officials, led by [[László Paskai]], [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Esztergom-Budapest|archbishop of Esztergom-Budapest]], strongly objected to Bulányi's teaching, considering it harmful and dangerous.{{sfn|Allen|2002|p=162}}{{sfn|Adogame|Olson|Obinna|Vincett|2016|p=149f}} They issued a formal condemnation of conscientious objection in October 1986.{{sfn|Miszlivetz|1999|p=12}} These officials supported government suppression of conscientious objectors,{{sfn|Allen|2002|p=162}} and imprisonments continued throughout the 1980s.{{sfn|Adogame|Olson|Obinna|Vincett|2016|p=149f}} Continued advocacy from groups like Bokor and interaction with Catholics outside of Hungary softened their perspective, however, and in March 1988, Paskai suggested that the Prime Minister allow [[alternative civilian service]].{{sfn|Miszlivetz|1999|p=12}} Paskai later claimed to have been constrained by the autocratic government and said that he had no choice but to collaborate in suppression.{{sfn|Allen|2002|p=162}}

== Conflict with Catholic hierarchy ==

The Hungarian government and Catholic hierarchy responded by seeking to discredit Bulányi by presenting evidence that his writings were heretical. There was significant debate about Bulányi's writings such as ''Church order'' and ''Is obedience a virtue?'', drawing input from theologians such as [[Hans Küng]].{{sfn|Zala Lama|2010}} In a 31 December 1986 letter, Cardinal [[Joseph Ratzinger]], head of the [[Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith]], asked Bulányi to publicly withdraw his teachings on the universal priesthood of the laity as false, dangerous ambiguous, and [[heretical]].{{sfn|Zala Lama|2010}}<ref name="Wagner" /><ref name="gerlo">[http://www.gerlo.hu/hvall/enci/bulanyi.html Ki tért meg? (Bulányi György piarista atya egyházi rehabilitációja, HVG, 1997. október 4.)]</ref> Bulányi did not agree with Ratzinger's assessment, and for a decade these strong official statements against Bulányi remained.{{sfn|Zala Lama|2010}} After the [[End of communism in Hungary (1989)|change in government in Hungary in 1989]], the Hungarian state requested forgiveness from Bulányi.<ref name="belfold" /> However, leaders of the Catholic Church did not apologize.<ref name="belfold">[https://index.hu/belfold/2010/06/07/meghalt_bulanyi_gyorgy/ Index.hu (Meghalt Bulányi György, 2010. június. 7.)]</ref>

Finally, in February 1997, Bulányi and Ratzinger came to an agreement, with [[John Paul II]] offering greater [[freedom of conscience]] than Ratzinger had previously accepted.{{cn|date=April 2018}} Bulányi cooperated, clarified his teachings, and signed a statement requested of him.{{sfn|Zala Lama|2010}} On 5 April 1997, Ratzinger wrote that he considered the matter closed.{{sfn|Zala Lama|2010}} On 10 September 1997, there was a public announcement of the formal [[Rehabilitation (Catholic)|rehabilitation]] of Bulányi in the Catholic Church,{{cn|date=April 2018}} and he was once again permitted to conduct mass.{{sfn|Ramet|2014|p=104}}

The [[Hungarian Catholic Bishops' Conference]] published the statements of Bulányi and Ratzinger without comment. Some Hungarian Catholics were disappointed that the Conference didn't offer an apology for their behavior toward Bulányi and his supporters. These Catholic viewed the actions of the Catholic hierarchy as improper use of power in collaboration with an immoral autocratic state.{{sfn|Zala Lama|2010}} Even after rehabilitation, Bulányi continued to be marginalized within the Catholic community.<ref>[http://nol.hu/belfold/bulanyi_gyorgy_halalara_ Népszabadság Online (Bulányi György halálára, 2010. June 7.)]</ref>{{sfn|Partizano|2010}} From 2005 until his death, Bulányi lived with other Piarists in the {{ill|Kalazantinum|hu}} of Budapest.{{cn|date=April 2018}}

== Views ==
Bulányi identified with the views of [[Marcion of Sinope]] in rejecting the [[Old Testament]] as [[Biblical inspiration|uninspired]], immoral, and incompatible with the character of the God of Jesus who is love.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=2014 |title=Az Ószövetség nem Isten igéje |trans-title=The Old Testament is not the Word of God |work=Flag Polgári Magazine |language=hu |url=https://flagmagazin.hu/mondom-a-magamet/bulanyi-gyorgy-atya-az-oszovetseg-nem-isten-igeje |access-date=16 April 2018}}, reprinted from an April issue of Magyar Mérce, published by [[Jobbik]].</ref>

Bulányi affirmed a church structure consisting of [[base communities]],<ref name="Wagner">[http://bocs.hu/ford/bocsf16.htm Idézi Jupp Wagner]</ref> based on a theological affirmation of [[universal priesthood]] of the [[laity]].{{sfn|Zala Lama|2010}}<ref>See also {{harvtxt|Ramet|2014|p=100}}</ref>

